Initially overwhelming, but I was able to get the hang of things and help the team see patients efficiently. I learned how handle and prioritize the many distractions we had.
Today was challenging in terms of readjusting to seeing pediatric patients. Eventually got the hand of it again.
Enjoyed the shift as I was able to do some procedures
Was able to do some procedures and was kept pretty busy through the night, which was good.
It was easier to follow Resus patients this time as I was less overwhelmed and knew the flow.
Difficult shift. It was a very slow night. Struggled with the plan for some patients.
Enjoyed this shift. Felt like an intern.
This was more exciting than the resus shift at Sinai. I felt more involved as well.
Adjusting to seeing patients at a different hospital was most challenging. Also having to use the interpreter phones all the time was challenging. I need to work on my Spanish.
This was a fun shift. I gelt like a real intern.
This wasn’t as exciting as I expected but again I was able to have more independence which was nice.
It was challenging to see patients you know should just go to the clinic but I always have to remember that people have different circumstances and should always be seen.
This shift was very slow initially and I had difficult patients, so remembering patience is key.
Very exciting shift since I finally saw some good traumas. It might be my thing.
Figuring out the ropes!. Very fun. Loved working with adolescent population. Yes— ID, rapid strep, straight catching baby, pelvic exam.
Feeling confident with orthopedic injuries. I’l like to get more comfortable with.
You have to be super persistent with making sure labs are sent and pain meds are given. I will make sure to be super ? at following up on my patients and finding out shot is their most ?
I felt more comfortable on this shift— was more efficient at managing multiple patients following up on labs. I learned that to determining true abdominal tenderness, distract the patient.

The time flew by. I enjoyed getting practice running a DNA PCR test for GC/Chlamydia. It was challenging to read a caretaker for a patin that we couldn’t ? I learned: 1) persistence pays off 2) Centor criteria 3) controversy/futility of antibiotics in otitis meda and Group A Strep.

Great exposure to come geriatric emergent complaints. I learned: 1) greater than 3 rib fractures = admit, insulin injections are difficulty for many geriatric patients ask about if they are having difficulty, it’s important X X X
I learned how to place an ultrasound guided IV. and how to manage frostbite. Rewarming is important. I will try ultrasound if the patient is a hard stick.

Dr. Olmeda found me a milliequivalent calculator. Took control for patients with X X pain is challenging. Deciding the appropriate doses and discriminating between drug seeking and true physical pain is done better with pain specialist involvement.
Placing an IV on elderly was challenging success with ultrasound-guided IV. Practiced peak flow and venipuncture. Learned about EKG in pulmonary disease.
If patient looks hyperglycemic can just get urinary dip to screen for ketones, the go home.
I think I did a good job identifying otitis media and counseling patients and their families.

I was proactive and learned practiced: reading practicing paracentesis, IV placement. It was challenging to keep track of certain labs. I had to be persistent in order to ger lab values that greatly impacted my management

I felt confident approaching patients on my own. I learned how to make a surgical consult maximally effective. I learned how to splint. I will offer Reglan to patient with heaves in the future. It seems to help a lot.

It was hard to evaluate back pain in a patient with a history of polio and neurological deficits. I was reminded about using Doppler to evaluate distal pulses that are difficult to palpate. I will make to to use the Doppler if I cannot find a pulse
Enjoyable pace; very challenging orthodox patient who only wanted to speak with Dr. Marcuse’s neurology resident, and so imposed a language barrier to limit care, nice mix of cases largely routine.

Challenging patient due to narcissistic personality disorder, lesson how social work needs and logistics can hinder movement through ER, got to do a pelvic exam, which was great. I don’t done OB/GYN in 1/5 years.

Good example of common problem (hand pain) taking up resources in ED instead of being seen by outpatient. Also had patient who wanted us to set up all appointments for non-emergent issues; good exercise to explain role of ER in her care

Did transvaginal ultrasound and found my sign very happy with that. Pelvic exam. Finger laceration. Good mix of patients. One pain in the ass patient who got her pain relief and came off not necessarily drug seeking, but definitely X X X X

Good mix of patients. Was sure patient had normal pressure hydrocephalus but was exacerbation of Parkinson’s. Reminded of how ou can really impact a patient when you attend to family and exhibit respect instead of just X them your X

Interesting case when patient was brought in with suspected appendicitis so surgery consulted and I examined with just that in mind. After Dr. Newman examined with fresh eye he realized not appendicitis. Good reminder to retain objectivity in face of other opinions.

Just felt off during shift— definitely struggled. For some reason I kept blanking on basic stuff. I think I should review a little more prior to presenting just to keep more in my head avoid brain freeze. But definitely provided good experience to my dialysis patients. Also felt like two patients were somewhat drug-seeking. Interesting to see how they thought they were X but were probably seeking.

Really slow shift— tried to look things up but no really a conducive environment. Had homeless patient frequent flyer but pleasant and cooperative. Still treat like potential MI I guess chest pain possible. But a slow shift.

Great X learning experience, patient with many risk factors for depression (breakup, abusive partner, poor social support) I though it was just open and shut depression. But thyroid workup showed elevated TSH leading to a new diagnosis of hypothyroid. Good reminder to look for organic causes of depression in addition to psychiatric causes.

Very combative patient who did not believe why or how he was forming a keloid scar, called me disrespectful and escalated to an uncomfortable degree. I felt like I did the best I could but nothing would change this guy, and sometimes you just have to let it go.

Great to have drug-seeking and alcoholic patient in this night. Good preparation for psychiatry. And good discussion on what to do for them. It is interesting how subtle the seeker thought she was but she was pretty obvious.

Very difficult migraine patient to much pain to do full neuro exam. Treated then finished exam. Anticipating response to meds. Difficult staff today— shifts are enormously more difficult depending on staff.

So much better when shift is faster and attending gives both autonomy and support. Watch patient 3 days post MI with DVT of UE leave against medical advice. Very disturbing but you can help people only as far as they will let you. For an overnight, good shift.

Had a patient who was clearly a hypochondriac exaggerating symptoms. Even though I knew she was just a dramatic girl, I still worked up up for a CVA for her headache. But I am annoyed that she wasted hospital resources. Just part of the job I guess.

Being efficient at history taking especially with translation was difficult. I think my presentations need to be focused much more. I am getting a sens of the art of triage and hope to develop this further.
Got to see a lot of good pathology
Am feeling better about taking control of my patients. Got on venipuncture/IV today
Was able to handle multiple patients simultaneously. Need to focus presentations further.
I think my presentations slowly improved in conciseness and focus. Didn’t do as many procedures today though

Tried to help out to my skill lever. Was able to perform compressions and assis in the differential diagnosis of pulseless electrical activity. Helped with ultrasound guided IV placement and other small procedures
Got a good exposure to pathology today.
Good exposure to procedures and basic outpatient procedures. Feel a bit more comfortable handling patients on my own even without supersivion
NA
NA
Was a bit stressful deciding what to do or triage with patients in distress. But a positive learning experience. Will avoid being burned by drug seekers in the future.
None
Good day, saw a range of pathology, will work on focusing presentations and write-ups further.
Slow day, but was able to perform some valuable follow up on previous patients to see how they did. Got genitourinary rectal exam experience today.
Great experience today, learned about X X X versus pathophysiology. Will try to better and X respond to X X
Excellent hands-on experience in Fast Track. Be more X and proactive.
Become clear and succinct with presentations
Work on X of clear anatomy and physiology
Excellent critical care experience. Continue reading about critical and and X X.
Continue to shorten history and physical
Excellent shifts
Great job today health X X X
Excellent succinct history and physicals. X X X good job with multiple patients
Excellent day learned about X X and Bell’s palsy. Good job with history and physicals.
Another good day learned a significant amount about disease pathology and sorting differentials for very X X
Slow X X X X Challenging to manage cases
Learn nuts and bolts of ER how to get things done (labs, scars, etc). Organize presentations (checklist).
Saw great variety today, Do not be afried to try arterial stick remember to read old notes
Start learning urgent doses: epinephrine, nor epinephrin, dopamine, keep asking why consider all differential diagnoses
Relevant data in oral presentaion
Thoroughly, thorough, thorough. Do not skip steps. Checklists.
Make a checklist for each patient and go over it before talking to attending (i.e. remember idap). Frequent flyers sometimes are really sick. Wheezing isn’t always asthma.
When to admit? What is the role of the Emergency Room in diagnosis? Make sure logistics happen
Team transition during resus
Standardize firms sheet to the physician
More organized history and physical helped a lot be thorough, undress if necessary
Talk to nurses, vouch for your patient when patient complains, listen, listen, listen
Try to talk face-to-face with consult teams. Consider is original diagnosis correct
Lucky to have interest patients but stay motivated regardless master checklist sure helpful
Bring to scans, get it done thorough always, follow-up religiously
First time seeing patients since November. Have to be quicker with history and physicals but overall nice to be back in the swing of things
Pretty busy but glad to be back in the swing of things, got to do 3 venipunctures and assist in intubation
Great diversity of cases, fall and head trauma, VZV, asthma attack, psychosis
Slow day in critical trauma brushed up on EKGs with Dr. Shah had a patient not stating well s/p intubation, turn out the endotracheal tube cuff was supraglottic
Great variety, alopecia, dog bites, incision and drainage of abscesses, contusion, motor vehicle accident
Successful shift lots of pneumonia influenza rule-outs Felt good to have a correct plan for each patient

Didn’t get to do much unfortunately. Great to see how an innovative geriatric emergency department works. even if no signs of history of head traym after an unmentioned fall always get a head CT to rule-out bleed.
Great variety of cases, lower back pain, gallstone pancreatitis, torticollis
Tough shift because of logistics with patient care. Even the nicest patients are liable to walk out. Miscommunication between GU residents.
first overnight shifts quicker than expected brushed up on Ottowa rules for imaging and otoscopy
Busy, got to do IVs, venipuncture, assisted in a code with chest compressions
Inguinal hernia recurrence. rule out acute coronary syndrome got to suture a huge 7cm facial laceration by m self which was awesome
Fascinating case of stroke-like symptoms in a patient with multiple medical complaint, lesson in prioritizing complaints and treatment plan

Priodontal abscess, physicall exam rule out angioedema secondary to ACE-inhibitor, fluorescing eye, dizziness after fall. Amazed by the variety emergency medicine does encounter and how you have to know a little of everything
great experience today not really challenging because only on resus learned a lot about stroke management
wonderful shift today loved the balance of independence and teaching
learned how to manage headache with intravenous vitamin E and then methylergonovine (the post-partum hemorrhage) thanks to super nice neurolgists
Geriatric emergency department is wonderful. Great pace. Learned patient with dementia is hard.
today I learned how to assess a sprained ankle to X-ray or not? bear weight?
Migraine management assessment of pseudo seizure were two thought-provoking pearls of today’s shift
Geri is my favorite unit, get to spend more time with patients and it is quieter. Practice reading EKGs with help from Dr. Heller
I appreciated individual and directed guidance X also helped me think through algorithm reasoning behind ordering D-dimers, very high yield
tonight was fun and educational but I wish it had been busier
really enjoyed getting to manage social issues today like oxygen tank and transport of patient and talk the patient about lifestyle changes
got to practice suturing
Had a great time educating a patient and her family about X medical complaints
it is really important to read old discharge notes
Know when to and when not to pursue diagnostic testing
Not many admits because hospital full learned a lot about the use of ultrasound in a spectrum of cases
Learning the system is a bit of a challenger. Had a spanish speaking patient daughter was translating switched to interpreter which helped
Review of lower gastrointestinal bleeding in liver patient was helpful isolating single acute complaint can be difficult need to get the patient focused
very busy assisted with central line on funded patient
saw a variety of patients, involved in laceration irrigation, head trauma after fall, wound check,
learned a lot from chest pain work-up consulted with the patient’s outside physician best to call social work consults early

difficult rotator cuff patient gave a patient a lecture on blood pressure physiology fun third intracranial bleed patient at this rotation
very busy 54 patient in emergency room on arrival good mix of patient severe fever syncope chest pain abdominal pain getting better at management of multiple patients simultaneously

got to suture a cheek it came out well good mix of patient abdominal pain, go bleed, constipation, solid shift

final shift second fast track shift Good procedure day: pilonidal abscess incision and drainage 2cm laceration sutured multiple intramuscular injections fun way to end the clerkship

learned to consider many things in abdominal pain differential diagnosis even if atypical presentation will remember this in fortune not all patients present typically
